Here is the complete design for P18-P24.

---

# Playbook patterns P18–P24 — design spec

The seven patterns below extend `references/html-patterns.md` so every body section of an equity-research playbook gets a treatment instead of falling through to prose. P21 and P22 promote the inline custom CSS already present in `ASML.html` (`.axis-card` and `.fm` / `.fm-tag`) into the formal catalogue so GOOG and future tickers (META, NFLX, AMZN) inherit them. Every pattern uses shell tokens only (`var(--accent)`, `var(--ok)`, `var(--danger)`, `var(--warn)`, `var(--info)`, `var(--muted)`, plus their `-soft` companions) so dark mode and print stay working with no per-ticker overrides.

A note on detection priority: P18–P24 should sit **after** P17 in the catalogue and the existing first-match-wins ordering means they only fire when an earlier pattern hasn't already claimed the section. P4 (NFR table) is the closest existing competitor for P18 / P20 / P24 — its detection trigger is `Target | SLO | p95 | Latency | Throughput | Availability | Budget` headers, none of which appear in playbook tables, so the patterns never collide. P17 (risks table) is the competitor for P22 (failure modes) — P17 fires on a markdown table with `Risk | Severity | Mitigation` headers; playbook failure modes are a bullet list with `[layer]` suffixes, so they never collide. Document this precedence explicitly in each pattern's text.

---

## P18 — Segment-mix horizontal stack bar

**Detect.** H2 text matches `/business architecture|segment mix|revenue mix/i` AND its body contains a markdown table whose first column header matches `/^segment$/i` (case-insensitive, trimmed) AND second column header contains `share` OR `%` OR `mix`. Detection trips at the table level — the pattern wraps the table with the chart, not the entire section. If only one of the two columns matches, the table falls through to prose. Avoids false positives in any non-playbook table that happens to use a generic "Segment" header by requiring the second-column share/percent signal as a hard co-condition.

**Choice: 100%-stacked horizontal bar over donut.** Donuts hide the long tail (slices below ~5% become unreadable arcs), require external legend mapping, and are awkward to print. A 100%-stacked horizontal bar reads left-to-right at any width, preserves the source-table ordering as labelled segments inside the bar, and prints cleanly. The source table sits directly below the bar and acts as the legend — no separate legend chip-row needed.

**Markdown shape.** Matches GOOG.md lines 36–44 and ASML.md lines 34–42 as-written. Zero markdown changes.

**HTML.**

```html
<div class="p-segmix">
  <svg class="p-segmix-bar" viewBox="0 0 400 32" preserveAspectRatio="none"
       role="img" aria-label="Revenue mix: Google Search 57%, YouTube Ads 11%, ...">
    <g>
      <rect x="0"   y="0" width="228" height="32" fill="var(--accent)"/>
      <rect x="228" y="0" width="44"  height="32" fill="var(--info)"/>
      <rect x="272" y="0" width="36"  height="32" fill="var(--warn)"/>
      <rect x="308" y="0" width="52"  height="32" fill="var(--ok)"/>
      <rect x="360" y="0" width="20"  height="32" fill="var(--danger)"/>
      <rect x="380" y="0" width="4"   height="32" fill="var(--muted)"/>
    </g>
    <g class="p-segmix-labels">
      <text x="114" y="20" text-anchor="middle">Search 57%</text>
      <text x="250" y="20" text-anchor="middle">YT 11%</text>
      <!-- omit text on slices <8% — table below carries the label -->
    </g>
  </svg>
  <!-- the original markdown table goes here, unchanged -->
  <table class="p-segmix-table">…</table>
</div>
```

The viewBox is `0 0 400 32` — the renderer normalises each segment's share to a 0–400 px x-axis. Labels render only on slices ≥ 8% to avoid overlap; the table beneath always carries the full label set.

**CSS.**

```css
.p-segmix { margin: 16px 0 22px; }
.p-segmix-bar { display: block; width: 100%; height: 32px; border-radius: 6px;
  overflow: hidden; border: 1px solid var(--rule); background: var(--surface); }
.p-segmix-bar rect { stroke: var(--bg); stroke-width: 1; }
.p-segmix-labels text { font: 700 11px/1 "Inter", ui-sans-serif, sans-serif;
  fill: var(--bg); letter-spacing: 0.02em; }
.p-segmix-table { margin-top: 10px; }
```

Slice colour cycle: `--accent, --info, --warn, --ok, --danger, --muted` in that order — six tokens, enough for every playbook seen so far. Label fill uses `var(--bg)` so it inverts in dark mode (light text on dark slice fill, dark text on light slice fill).

**Accessibility.** `role="img"` with an `aria-label` that lists every segment and share. The source `<table>` is the canonical data — screen readers reading the table get the full picture regardless of the bar's rendering.

**When to use.** Playbook §1 with a Segment / Revenue share table.
**When not to use.** Tables with >8 segments (the bar becomes unreadable) — fall through to prose. Tables whose share column is a range like "5–10%" (the bar can't render a range) — fall through to prose. The detection rule already enforces a numeric share format, but the pattern implementation should defensively detect ranges and skip.

**Verification.** Open both GOOG.html and ASML.html: bar widths sum to 100% of container; slice colours follow the six-token cycle; table is fully visible below; dark mode inverts the label text contrast; print renders the bar at black-and-white-distinguishable shades (the six tokens have distinct luminance, so this works without further effort).

---

## P19 — Margin position-band strip

**Detect (strict, to avoid false positives).** H2 text matches `/(capex|AI investment) cycle|cycle position|normalised margin|investment cycle/i` AND a single paragraph within the section contains all three of:

1. A keyword phrase matching `/normalis(ed|ation)|anchor|floor|ceiling|midpoint|sits between|range from/i`;
2. At least two numeric anchors of the form `\d+(\.\d+)?\s*%` within the same paragraph;
3. The numeric anchors are within 250 characters of each other.

All three are required — keyword-only or numbers-only paragraphs fall through to prose. The strict trigger is the cost of avoiding false positives in DCF prose, which is dense with `%` figures that aren't position anchors. The renderer extracts the numeric anchors in source order and labels them by proximity-to-nearest-keyword: `floor → low end`, `ceiling → high end`, `base / anchor / midpoint → marked tick`, otherwise positional fallback (lowest = floor, highest = ceiling).

**Markdown shape.** Matches GOOG.md §2 "Normalised-margin anchors" paragraph and ASML.md §2 "Normalised-margin thesis" paragraph as-written. Zero markdown changes.

**HTML.** A horizontal strip with two endpoint labels and a marker tick:

```html
<figure class="p-band">
  <figcaption class="p-band-cap">Terminal margin anchors (SBC-stripped FCF basis)</figcaption>
  <div class="p-band-strip" role="img"
       aria-label="Range: floor 22–27%, base 30%, ceiling 35%+. Base sits at 30%.">
    <div class="p-band-track">
      <div class="p-band-fill" style="left:0%;width:100%"></div>
      <div class="p-band-tick" style="left:62%"><span>30%</span></div>
    </div>
    <div class="p-band-ends">
      <span class="p-band-low">22–27%<br><em>normalised-FCF floor</em></span>
      <span class="p-band-high">35%+<br><em>Search-segment ceiling</em></span>
    </div>
  </div>
</figure>
```

The renderer computes `left:` for the base tick as `(base - low) / (high - low) * 100%`. When the source paragraph carries explicit floor/ceiling/base labels (most playbooks do), those become the end-label `<em>` lines; otherwise the labels are omitted and the strip shows numbers only.

**CSS.**

```css
.p-band { margin: 20px 0 22px; max-width: 640px; }
.p-band-cap { font: 700 12px/1 "Inter", ui-sans-serif, sans-serif;
  letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--muted);
  margin-bottom: 12px; }
.p-band-strip { position: relative; padding: 12px 0 4px; }
.p-band-track { position: relative; height: 10px; border-radius: 5px;
  background: var(--rule-soft); border: 1px solid var(--rule); }
.p-band-fill { position: absolute; top: 0; bottom: 0;
  background: linear-gradient(90deg, var(--danger-soft), var(--warn-soft), var(--ok-soft));
  border-radius: 5px; }
.p-band-tick { position: absolute; top: -6px; width: 2px; height: 22px;
  background: var(--accent); transform: translateX(-1px); }
.p-band-tick span { position: absolute; top: -22px; left: 50%;
  transform: translateX(-50%); font: 700 12px/1 ui-monospace, monospace;
  color: var(--accent); white-space: nowrap; background: var(--bg);
  padding: 0 4px; }
.p-band-ends { display: flex; justify-content: space-between;
  margin-top: 10px; font-size: 12.5px; color: var(--muted); }
.p-band-ends em { display: block; font-style: normal; color: var(--fg-soft);
  font-size: 12px; }
.p-band-low { text-align: left; } .p-band-high { text-align: right; }
```

Gradient track uses red-yellow-green soft tokens — the visual reading is "the band spans distress → comfort and the base tick is here". Works in dark mode because all four tokens (`--danger-soft`, `--warn-soft`, `--ok-soft`, `--accent`) have dark-mode companions in the skeleton.

**Accessibility.** `role="img"` with a full `aria-label`. The source paragraph stays in the DOM unchanged immediately after the figure — screen readers get the prose narrative.

**When to use.** A §2-style paragraph with explicit floor/base/ceiling language and two-or-more percentage anchors.
**When not to use.** A paragraph that just lists historical margins without a "between" or "anchor" framing — the strict trigger keeps these out. If the renderer can't extract three numeric anchors confidently, fall through to prose; don't render a strip with only two numbers (it's just a range bar with no story).

**Verification.** Tick position visually matches `(base - low) / (high - low)`; gradient renders in dark mode; the source paragraph still appears unchanged underneath; the `aria-label` reads the anchors in numeric order.

---

## P20 — Catalyst probability × IV-impact mini-bars

**Detect.** H2 matches `/catalysts?|near[- ]term catalysts?|upcoming catalysts/i` AND a markdown table whose header row contains all three of (case-insensitive): `catalyst`, `probability` (or `prob`), `IV impact` (or `impact`).

**Choice: inline mini-bars over scatter.** A scatter plot with 8 catalyst points loses point identity (labels overlap, hover doesn't work in static HTML), and either the labels become unreadable or the chart becomes a connect-the-dots puzzle. Inline mini-bars on each row preserve identity, keep the table as the primary structure, and scan top-to-bottom — the order in which the analyst wrote them. The renderer parses `~35%` as 35, `~15–25%` as the midpoint 20, into a 0–100 probability value and `±10–20%` as the absolute midpoint (15) signed by the direction column.

**Markdown shape.** Matches GOOG.md §3 and ASML.md §3 as-written. Zero markdown changes.

**HTML.** Standard `<table>` with `class="p-catalysts"` plus two additional virtual columns inserted (`<th class="p-cat-prob-bar">` and `<th class="p-cat-iv-bar">`) carrying the bars:

```html
<table class="p-catalysts">
  <thead><tr>
    <th>Catalyst</th><th>Probability</th><th></th>
    <th>IV impact</th><th></th><th>Direction</th>
  </tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>DOJ Search remedies finalised…</td>
      <td class="p-num">~35%</td>
      <td class="p-cat-bar-cell"><span class="p-cat-bar p-cat-bar-prob"
        style="--w:35%"></span></td>
      <td class="p-num">−10–20%</td>
      <td class="p-cat-bar-cell">
        <span class="p-cat-bar p-cat-bar-iv p-cat-bar-neg" style="--w:15%"></span>
      </td>
      <td><span class="p-cat-dir p-cat-dir-neg">↓ Negative</span></td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
```

The IV-impact bar's width is the absolute midpoint of the range, capped at 30% for visual normalisation (anything >30% saturates the bar — and >30% IV swings are rare).

**CSS.**

```css
.p-catalysts td.p-num { font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, monospace;
  text-align: right; white-space: nowrap; }
.p-catalysts .p-cat-bar-cell { width: 80px; padding: 8px; }
.p-cat-bar { display: block; height: 8px; width: var(--w); border-radius: 4px;
  min-width: 6px; }
.p-cat-bar-prob { background: var(--info); }
.p-cat-bar-iv.p-cat-bar-pos { background: var(--ok); }
.p-cat-bar-iv.p-cat-bar-neg { background: var(--danger); }
.p-cat-dir { font: 700 12px/1 "Inter", ui-sans-serif, sans-serif;
  letter-spacing: 0.04em; padding: 4px 8px; border-radius: 4px; white-space: nowrap; }
.p-cat-dir-pos { background: var(--ok-soft); color: var(--ok); }
.p-cat-dir-neg { background: var(--danger-soft); color: var(--danger); }
.p-cat-dir-mixed { background: var(--warn-soft); color: var(--warn); }
```

**Accessibility.** Real `<table>` with `<thead>` / `<tbody>`; the bar `<span>`s are decorative — the numeric cells next to them carry the meaning. `--w` via CSS custom property keeps the inline style minimal and parsable.

**When to use.** §3-style catalyst tables in any playbook.
**When not to use.** Catalyst tables without a Probability column (the bars are the point of the pattern) — fall through to P4 numeric-table treatment.

**Verification.** Bar widths visually match the percentage cells; direction pills use the correct token; probability bars are uniform colour; IV-impact bars carry the green/red sign.

