## P23 — Scenario-axes shape plot *(reads from frontmatter, not body)*

**Detect.** This pattern is unusual: it does not detect on body markdown shape. Instead, it activates whenever the renderer's frontmatter parser (P9) produces a `scenario_axes` field with at least one of `bear.{growth_ceiling, terminal_margin}` or `bull.{growth_ceiling, terminal_margin}` populated. The plot lifts into the body once, immediately under the §6 H2 (which is matched separately by header text `/overrides|rationale/i`). If §6 isn't present, the plot lifts immediately before §1.

**Why this special-case.** `scenario_axes` is data, not prose. It exists to describe the asymmetric shape of bear / base / bull on a (growth × margin) plane. Both GOOG and ASML explain this shape verbally in their §6 rationale prose. A small SVG plot replaces the need to read three paragraphs to picture three points.

**Data extraction from frontmatter.** Frontmatter fields used:

```yaml
growth_ceiling: 0.13                # base
terminal_margin: 0.30               # base
scenario_axes:
  bear:
    growth_ceiling: 0.04            # bear override (else fall back to base × 0.6)
    terminal_margin: 0.22           # bear override (else fall back to base − 5pp)
  bull:
    growth_ceiling: 0.18            # bull override (else fall back to base × 1.3)
    terminal_margin: 0.32           # bull override (else fall back to base + 3pp)
```

When ASML's frontmatter omits `bear.growth_ceiling` and `bull.terminal_margin`, the renderer uses the documented `±multiplier` fallback (which is what the DCF loader itself uses) so the plot visualises the same shape the DCF actually computes. The fallback formulas should be added to the catalogue entry verbatim so they stay stable.

**HTML.**

```html
