# Playbook patterns P18–P24 — design spec

The seven patterns below extend `references/html-patterns.md` so every body section of an equity-research playbook gets a treatment instead of falling through to prose. P21 and P22 promote the inline custom CSS already present in `ASML.html` (`.axis-card` and `.fm` / `.fm-tag`) into the formal catalogue so GOOG and future tickers (META, NFLX, AMZN) inherit them. Every pattern uses shell tokens only (`var(--accent)`, `var(--ok)`, `var(--danger)`, `var(--warn)`, `var(--info)`, `var(--muted)`, plus their `-soft` companions) so dark mode and print stay working with no per-ticker overrides.

A note on detection priority: P18–P24 should sit **after** P17 in the catalogue and the existing first-match-wins ordering means they only fire when an earlier pattern hasn't already claimed the section. P4 (NFR table) is the closest existing competitor for P18 / P20 / P24 — its detection trigger is `Target | SLO | p95 | Latency | Throughput | Availability | Budget` headers, none of which appear in playbook tables, so the patterns never collide. P17 (risks table) is the competitor for P22 (failure modes) — P17 fires on a markdown table with `Risk | Severity | Mitigation` headers; playbook failure modes are a bullet list with `[layer]` suffixes, so they never collide. Document this precedence explicitly in each pattern's text.

