## P18 — Segment-mix horizontal stack bar

**Detect.** H2 text matches `/business architecture|segment mix|revenue mix/i` AND its body contains a markdown table whose first column header matches `/^segment$/i` (case-insensitive, trimmed) AND second column header contains `share` OR `%` OR `mix`. Detection trips at the table level — the pattern wraps the table with the chart, not the entire section. If only one of the two columns matches, the table falls through to prose. Avoids false positives in any non-playbook table that happens to use a generic "Segment" header by requiring the second-column share/percent signal as a hard co-condition.

**Choice: 100%-stacked horizontal bar over donut.** Donuts hide the long tail (slices below ~5% become unreadable arcs), require external legend mapping, and are awkward to print. A 100%-stacked horizontal bar reads left-to-right at any width, preserves the source-table ordering as labelled segments inside the bar, and prints cleanly. The source table sits directly below the bar and acts as the legend — no separate legend chip-row needed.

**Markdown shape.** Matches GOOG.md lines 36–44 and ASML.md lines 34–42 as-written. Zero markdown changes.

**HTML.**

```html
<div class="p-segmix">
  <svg class="p-segmix-bar" viewBox="0 0 400 32" preserveAspectRatio="none"
       role="img" aria-label="Revenue mix: Google Search 57%, YouTube Ads 11%, ...">
    <g>
      <rect x="0"   y="0" width="228" height="32" fill="var(--accent)"/>
      <rect x="228" y="0" width="44"  height="32" fill="var(--info)"/>
      <rect x="272" y="0" width="36"  height="32" fill="var(--warn)"/>
      <rect x="308" y="0" width="52"  height="32" fill="var(--ok)"/>
      <rect x="360" y="0" width="20"  height="32" fill="var(--danger)"/>
      <rect x="380" y="0" width="4"   height="32" fill="var(--muted)"/>
    </g>
    <g class="p-segmix-labels">
      <text x="114" y="20" text-anchor="middle">Search 57%</text>
      <text x="250" y="20" text-anchor="middle">YT 11%</text>
      <!-- omit text on slices <8% — table below carries the label -->
    </g>
  </svg>
  <!-- the original markdown table goes here, unchanged -->
  <table class="p-segmix-table">…</table>
</div>
```

The viewBox is `0 0 400 32` — the renderer normalises each segment's share to a 0–400 px x-axis. Labels render only on slices ≥ 8% to avoid overlap; the table beneath always carries the full label set.

**CSS.**

```css
.p-segmix { margin: 16px 0 22px; }
.p-segmix-bar { display: block; width: 100%; height: 32px; border-radius: 6px;
  overflow: hidden; border: 1px solid var(--rule); background: var(--surface); }
.p-segmix-bar rect { stroke: var(--bg); stroke-width: 1; }
.p-segmix-labels text { font: 700 11px/1 "Inter", ui-sans-serif, sans-serif;
  fill: var(--bg); letter-spacing: 0.02em; }
.p-segmix-table { margin-top: 10px; }
```

Slice colour cycle: `--accent, --info, --warn, --ok, --danger, --muted` in that order — six tokens, enough for every playbook seen so far. Label fill uses `var(--bg)` so it inverts in dark mode (light text on dark slice fill, dark text on light slice fill).

**Accessibility.** `role="img"` with an `aria-label` that lists every segment and share. The source `<table>` is the canonical data — screen readers reading the table get the full picture regardless of the bar's rendering.

**When to use.** Playbook §1 with a Segment / Revenue share table.
**When not to use.** Tables with >8 segments (the bar becomes unreadable) — fall through to prose. Tables whose share column is a range like "5–10%" (the bar can't render a range) — fall through to prose. The detection rule already enforces a numeric share format, but the pattern implementation should defensively detect ranges and skip.

**Verification.** Open both GOOG.html and ASML.html: bar widths sum to 100% of container; slice colours follow the six-token cycle; table is fully visible below; dark mode inverts the label text contrast; print renders the bar at black-and-white-distinguishable shades (the six tokens have distinct luminance, so this works without further effort).

