## P19 — Margin position-band strip

**Detect (strict, to avoid false positives).** H2 text matches `/(capex|AI investment) cycle|cycle position|normalised margin|investment cycle/i` AND a single paragraph within the section contains all three of:

1. A keyword phrase matching `/normalis(ed|ation)|anchor|floor|ceiling|midpoint|sits between|range from/i`;
2. At least two numeric anchors of the form `\d+(\.\d+)?\s*%` within the same paragraph;
3. The numeric anchors are within 250 characters of each other.

All three are required — keyword-only or numbers-only paragraphs fall through to prose. The strict trigger is the cost of avoiding false positives in DCF prose, which is dense with `%` figures that aren't position anchors. The renderer extracts the numeric anchors in source order and labels them by proximity-to-nearest-keyword: `floor → low end`, `ceiling → high end`, `base / anchor / midpoint → marked tick`, otherwise positional fallback (lowest = floor, highest = ceiling).

**Markdown shape.** Matches GOOG.md §2 "Normalised-margin anchors" paragraph and ASML.md §2 "Normalised-margin thesis" paragraph as-written. Zero markdown changes.

**HTML.** A horizontal strip with two endpoint labels and a marker tick:

```html
<figure class="p-band">
  <figcaption class="p-band-cap">Terminal margin anchors (SBC-stripped FCF basis)</figcaption>
  <div class="p-band-strip" role="img"
       aria-label="Range: floor 22–27%, base 30%, ceiling 35%+. Base sits at 30%.">
    <div class="p-band-track">
      <div class="p-band-fill" style="left:0%;width:100%"></div>
      <div class="p-band-tick" style="left:62%"><span>30%</span></div>
    </div>
    <div class="p-band-ends">
      <span class="p-band-low">22–27%<br><em>normalised-FCF floor</em></span>
      <span class="p-band-high">35%+<br><em>Search-segment ceiling</em></span>
    </div>
  </div>
</figure>
```

The renderer computes `left:` for the base tick as `(base - low) / (high - low) * 100%`. When the source paragraph carries explicit floor/ceiling/base labels (most playbooks do), those become the end-label `<em>` lines; otherwise the labels are omitted and the strip shows numbers only.

**CSS.**

```css
.p-band { margin: 20px 0 22px; max-width: 640px; }
.p-band-cap { font: 700 12px/1 "Inter", ui-sans-serif, sans-serif;
  letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--muted);
  margin-bottom: 12px; }
.p-band-strip { position: relative; padding: 12px 0 4px; }
.p-band-track { position: relative; height: 10px; border-radius: 5px;
  background: var(--rule-soft); border: 1px solid var(--rule); }
.p-band-fill { position: absolute; top: 0; bottom: 0;
  background: linear-gradient(90deg, var(--danger-soft), var(--warn-soft), var(--ok-soft));
  border-radius: 5px; }
.p-band-tick { position: absolute; top: -6px; width: 2px; height: 22px;
  background: var(--accent); transform: translateX(-1px); }
.p-band-tick span { position: absolute; top: -22px; left: 50%;
  transform: translateX(-50%); font: 700 12px/1 ui-monospace, monospace;
  color: var(--accent); white-space: nowrap; background: var(--bg);
  padding: 0 4px; }
.p-band-ends { display: flex; justify-content: space-between;
  margin-top: 10px; font-size: 12.5px; color: var(--muted); }
.p-band-ends em { display: block; font-style: normal; color: var(--fg-soft);
  font-size: 12px; }
.p-band-low { text-align: left; } .p-band-high { text-align: right; }
```

Gradient track uses red-yellow-green soft tokens — the visual reading is "the band spans distress → comfort and the base tick is here". Works in dark mode because all four tokens (`--danger-soft`, `--warn-soft`, `--ok-soft`, `--accent`) have dark-mode companions in the skeleton.

**Accessibility.** `role="img"` with a full `aria-label`. The source paragraph stays in the DOM unchanged immediately after the figure — screen readers get the prose narrative.

**When to use.** A §2-style paragraph with explicit floor/base/ceiling language and two-or-more percentage anchors.
**When not to use.** A paragraph that just lists historical margins without a "between" or "anchor" framing — the strict trigger keeps these out. If the renderer can't extract three numeric anchors confidently, fall through to prose; don't render a strip with only two numbers (it's just a range bar with no story).

**Verification.** Tick position visually matches `(base - low) / (high - low)`; gradient renders in dark mode; the source paragraph still appears unchanged underneath; the `aria-label` reads the anchors in numeric order.

