.p-fm-tag { font: 700 10.5px/1 "Inter", ui-sans-serif, sans-serif;
  letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase; padding: 5px 10px;
  border-radius: 4px; white-space: nowrap; align-self: start; margin-top: 2px; }
.p-fm-tag-interface     { background: var(--accent-soft); color: var(--accent); }
.p-fm-tag-monetisation,
.p-fm-tag-monetization  { background: var(--info-soft);   color: var(--info); }
.p-fm-tag-cost          { background: var(--warn-soft);   color: var(--warn); }
.p-fm-tag-ecosystem     { background: var(--info-soft);   color: var(--info); }
.p-fm-tag-demand        { background: var(--danger-soft); color: var(--danger); }
.p-fm-tag-regulatory    { background: var(--warn-soft);   color: var(--warn); }
.p-fm-tag-technology    { background: var(--accent-soft); color: var(--accent); }
.p-fm-tag-accounting,
.p-fm-tag-other         { background: var(--rule-soft);   color: var(--muted); }
.p-fm-tag-fx            { background: var(--info-soft);   color: var(--info); }
```

**Accessibility.** `<ul>` semantics preserved; tag `<span>` carries the layer text; the card grid is purely visual. Legend is `aria-hidden`; the tags inside each card carry the meaning for screen readers.

**Precedence.** P22 ranks above P17 inside playbook documents. P17 detects a table with `Risk | Sev | Mitigation` headers; P22 detects bullets with `[xxx layer]` tags. The two never co-trigger in practice because playbook failure-mode sections are always bullets, never tables.

**Migration note (ASML.html → P22 markdown).** The ASML.html `<div class="fm-list">…</div>` block (lines 472–497) can be deleted entirely; the markdown source already carries the canonical form. The renderer's tag-extraction regex (`/\[([a-zA-Z]+) layer\]\s*$/`) reads from the bullet's trailing text. No new markdown is required.

**When to use.** Playbook §5. Any future ticker bullet-list where modes end with `[xxx layer]` tags.
**When not to use.** Failure-mode sections rendered as a `<table>` — that goes to P17. Bullets without layer tags — fall through to prose.

**Verification.** Legend shows the unique set of layers present; each card carries its tag; colours match the palette table above; unknown layers fall to the `-other` muted style; dark mode preserves all tag contrasts (the soft companions all have dark-mode versions).

---

## P23 — Scenario-axes shape plot *(reads from frontmatter, not body)*

**Detect.** This pattern is unusual: it does not detect on body markdown shape. Instead, it activates whenever the renderer's frontmatter parser (P9) produces a `scenario_axes` field with at least one of `bear.{growth_ceiling, terminal_margin}` or `bull.{growth_ceiling, terminal_margin}` populated. The plot lifts into the body once, immediately under the §6 H2 (which is matched separately by header text `/overrides|rationale/i`). If §6 isn't present, the plot lifts immediately before §1.

**Why this special-case.** `scenario_axes` is data, not prose. It exists to describe the asymmetric shape of bear / base / bull on a (growth × margin) plane. Both GOOG and ASML explain this shape verbally in their §6 rationale prose. A small SVG plot replaces the need to read three paragraphs to picture three points.

**Data extraction from frontmatter.** Frontmatter fields used:

```yaml
growth_ceiling: 0.13                # base
terminal_margin: 0.30               # base
scenario_axes:
  bear:
    growth_ceiling: 0.04            # bear override (else fall back to base × 0.6)
    terminal_margin: 0.22           # bear override (else fall back to base − 5pp)
  bull:
    growth_ceiling: 0.18            # bull override (else fall back to base × 1.3)
    terminal_margin: 0.32           # bull override (else fall back to base + 3pp)
```

When ASML's frontmatter omits `bear.growth_ceiling` and `bull.terminal_margin`, the renderer uses the documented `±multiplier` fallback (which is what the DCF loader itself uses) so the plot visualises the same shape the DCF actually computes. The fallback formulas should be added to the catalogue entry verbatim so they stay stable.

**HTML.**

```html
<figure class="p-scenshape">
  <figcaption class="p-scenshape-cap">Scenario shape · growth ceiling × terminal margin</figcaption>
  <svg viewBox="0 0 320 240" role="img"
       aria-label="Bear: growth 4%, margin 22%. Base: growth 13%, margin 30%. Bull: growth 18%, margin 32%.">
    <!-- gridlines -->
    <g class="p-scenshape-grid">
      <line x1="40" y1="20"  x2="40"  y2="200"/>
      <line x1="40" y1="200" x2="300" y2="200"/>
      <line x1="40" y1="110" x2="300" y2="110" stroke-dasharray="2 3"/>
      <line x1="170" y1="20" x2="170" y2="200" stroke-dasharray="2 3"/>
    </g>
    <!-- axis labels -->
    <text x="170" y="230" text-anchor="middle" class="p-scenshape-axis">growth ceiling →</text>
    <text x="20" y="110" text-anchor="middle" transform="rotate(-90,20,110)" class="p-scenshape-axis">terminal margin →</text>
    <!-- polygon connecting bear → base → bull -->
    <polygon points="65,180 200,80 260,60"
             fill="var(--accent-soft)" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
    <!-- three points + labels -->
    <circle cx="65"  cy="180" r="6" fill="var(--danger)"/>
    <text   x="65"   y="200" text-anchor="middle" class="p-scenshape-pt">Bear (4%, 22%)</text>
    <circle cx="200" cy="80"  r="6" fill="var(--accent)"/>
    <text   x="200"  y="68"  text-anchor="middle" class="p-scenshape-pt">Base (13%, 30%)</text>
    <circle cx="260" cy="60"  r="6" fill="var(--ok)"/>
    <text   x="260"  y="48"  text-anchor="middle" class="p-scenshape-pt">Bull (18%, 32%)</text>
  </svg>
</figure>
```

The plot uses fixed-range axes: growth `0%–25%` (x-axis spans `40–300 px`), terminal margin `15%–40%` (y-axis spans `200–20 px`). These ranges cover every coverage ticker — META has growth_ceiling up to ~22% in bull, ASML margins down to 24% in bear. The renderer normalises each point's coordinates with the formula in the catalogue entry. The `<polygon>` connects the three points in canonical order (bear → base → bull) so the shape's asymmetry — symmetric ±delta = isoceles triangle on the diagonal; structural-break shape = elongated or skewed triangle — is visible at a glance.

**CSS.**

```css
.p-scenshape { margin: 22px 0; background: var(--surface);
  border: 1px solid var(--rule); border-radius: 10px;
  padding: 20px 22px; max-width: 480px; }
.p-scenshape-cap { font: 700 12px/1 "Inter", ui-sans-serif, sans-serif;
  letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase;
  color: var(--muted); margin-bottom: 14px; }
.p-scenshape svg { display: block; width: 100%; height: auto; }
.p-scenshape-grid line { stroke: var(--rule); stroke-width: 1; fill: none; }
.p-scenshape-axis { font: 11px ui-monospace, monospace; fill: var(--muted); }
.p-scenshape-pt { font: 11px ui-monospace, monospace; fill: var(--fg-soft); }
```

**Accessibility.** `role="img"` with full `aria-label` describing all three scenario points. The figure is supplementary; the source `scenario_axes` rationale prose (already in §6 §6 body) carries the canonical explanation.

**When to use.** Any playbook frontmatter with a `scenario_axes:` block. Both GOOG and ASML qualify today; META currently does not have one populated but should activate once one is added.
**When not to use.** Frontmatter without `scenario_axes`. No fallback shape — the plot's value comes from comparing bear/base/bull positions.

**Verification.** Three dots positioned consistent with the values in frontmatter; bear dot is bottom-left of base, bull dot is top-right (in the typical case); polygon fill is accent-soft; the label `aria-label` reads the three numeric pairs.

---

## P24 — Reset-and-recover timeline

**Detect.** H2 matches `/historical reset|reset[- ]and[- ]recover|recovery prior|historical prior/i` AND a markdown table whose header row contains all three of (case-insensitive): `episode`, `drawdown`, `recovery`. Optional further columns (`catalyst`, `lesson`) are preserved as the row's caption text.

**Choice: scatter plot over horizontal time-bar.** A horizontal time-bar requires precise start/end dates per episode; the source data is `~−45% peak-to-trough` and `~12 months recovery` — magnitude and duration, not calendar bounds. A scatter on `(recovery duration, drawdown magnitude)` reads as "how deep × how long" — exactly the dimensions the analyst is communicating. The original table sits below as the canonical legend.

**Data extraction.** From each row, the renderer parses:
- `drawdown_pct = abs(int from /~?−?\d+/)` matched in the Drawdown cell, taking the upper end of any range (`−20–25%` → 25);
- `recovery_months = int from /~?\d+/` matched in the Recovery cell (`~14 months` → 14, `Partial recovery` → fallback 18 to bias toward "longer");
- `episode = trimmed Episode cell`.

**Markdown shape.** Matches GOOG.md §7 (3 rows) and ASML.md §7 (3 rows) as-written. Zero markdown changes.

**HTML.**

```html
<figure class="p-resets">
  <figcaption class="p-resets-cap">Reset depth × recovery duration</figcaption>
  <svg viewBox="0 0 480 240" role="img"
       aria-label="2022 ad recession: 45% drawdown, 12 months recovery. 2023 Bing/ChatGPT scare: 15%, 6 months. 2024 DOJ + AI-Mode: 25%, 18 months.">
    <!-- axes -->
    <line x1="50" y1="200" x2="460" y2="200" stroke="var(--rule)"/>
    <line x1="50" y1="200" x2="50"  y2="30"  stroke="var(--rule)"/>
    <!-- gridlines at 20%/40%/60% drawdown -->
    <line x1="50" y1="160" x2="460" y2="160" stroke="var(--rule)" stroke-dasharray="2 3"/>
    <line x1="50" y1="120" x2="460" y2="120" stroke="var(--rule)" stroke-dasharray="2 3"/>
    <line x1="50" y1="80"  x2="460" y2="80"  stroke="var(--rule)" stroke-dasharray="2 3"/>
    <!-- axis labels -->
    <text x="255" y="230" text-anchor="middle" class="p-resets-axis">recovery (months)</text>
    <text x="30"  y="115" text-anchor="middle" transform="rotate(-90,30,115)"
          class="p-resets-axis">drawdown %</text>
    <!-- tick labels -->
    <text x="50" y="216"  text-anchor="middle" class="p-resets-tick">0</text>
    <text x="155" y="216" text-anchor="middle" class="p-resets-tick">6</text>
    <text x="255" y="216" text-anchor="middle" class="p-resets-tick">12</text>
    <text x="360" y="216" text-anchor="middle" class="p-resets-tick">18</text>
    <text x="460" y="216" text-anchor="middle" class="p-resets-tick">24</text>
    <text x="44" y="204" text-anchor="end" class="p-resets-tick">0</text>
    <text x="44" y="164" text-anchor="end" class="p-resets-tick">20</text>
    <text x="44" y="124" text-anchor="end" class="p-resets-tick">40</text>
    <text x="44" y="84"  text-anchor="end" class="p-resets-tick">60</text>
    <!-- one point per episode -->
    <g class="p-resets-pt">
      <circle cx="255" cy="110" r="7" fill="var(--danger)"/>
      <text x="265" y="106" class="p-resets-lbl">2022 ad recession (−45%, 12m)</text>
    </g>
    <g class="p-resets-pt">
      <circle cx="155" cy="170" r="7" fill="var(--warn)"/>
      <text x="165" y="166" class="p-resets-lbl">2023 Bing+ChatGPT scare (−15%, 6m)</text>
    </g>
    <g class="p-resets-pt">
      <circle cx="360" cy="150" r="7" fill="var(--warn)"/>
      <text x="370" y="146" class="p-resets-lbl">2024 DOJ + AI-Mode (−25%, 18m)</text>
    </g>
  </svg>
  <!-- the original source table goes here, unchanged -->
  <table class="p-resets-table">…</table>
</figure>
```

Point colour follows drawdown severity bands: `≤20% → --warn`, `20–40% → --danger`, `>40% → --danger` filled with extra opacity. Three colour bands keep the chart readable in print without losing the severity signal.

**CSS.**

```css
.p-resets { margin: 22px 0; }
.p-resets-cap { font: 700 12px/1 "Inter", ui-sans-serif, sans-serif;
  letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase;
  color: var(--muted); margin-bottom: 14px; }
.p-resets svg { display: block; max-width: 720px; width: 100%;
  height: auto; background: var(--surface);
  border: 1px solid var(--rule); border-radius: 10px;
  padding: 8px; box-sizing: content-box; }
.p-resets-axis { font: 11.5px ui-monospace, monospace; fill: var(--muted); }
.p-resets-tick { font: 10.5px ui-monospace, monospace; fill: var(--muted); }
.p-resets-lbl { font: 11.5px "Inter", ui-sans-serif, sans-serif;
  fill: var(--fg-soft); }
.p-resets-table { margin-top: 14px; }
```

**Accessibility.** `role="img"` with a full `aria-label` enumerating each point. The source table is canonical — chart is supplementary.

**When to use.** Playbook §7 with the standard 3-row episode table.
**When not to use.** If a row's drawdown or recovery cell can't be parsed numerically (the renderer can't place the dot), drop just that point and keep the rest of the chart. If fewer than 2 points are plottable, fall through to prose + table.

**Verification.** Each dot's `(x, y)` matches the formula `(months × 17.5 + 50, 200 − drawdown_pct × 2)`; label text doesn't overlap; severity colours map correctly; the source table is fully present and unchanged underneath.

---

## Slicing recommendation — three implementation slices

The slicing strategy puts the lowest-risk migrations first so the renderer infrastructure is exercised under known-correct conditions before any new visual logic ships.

**Slice 1 — promotions only (P21 + P22).** Lift the ASML inline CSS into the catalogue and re-key class names. No new visual logic; the rendering tree is what ASML.html already produces, just driven from markdown instead of hand-authored HTML. Token-binding (`#f0fdf4 → var(--ok-soft)`, `#fee2e2 → var(--danger-soft)`, etc.) means dark mode starts working everywhere it didn't before. GOOG.html immediately gains both sections. The verification surface is two playbooks × two sections = four cases; each is visually comparable to the existing ASML.html snapshot. Risk: low. Dependencies: needs the renderer to be able to detect H3 axis cards and bullet-with-trailing-tag — both straightforward regex.

**Slice 2 — table-driven inline charts (P18 + P20 + P24).** Three patterns that all extract data from existing markdown tables and decorate the table with inline SVG. Common implementation primitive: a "numeric-cell parser" that converts cells like `~35%`, `−10–20%`, `~14 months` into numeric values. Build the parser once, then each pattern is ~30 lines of SVG-generation. No detection ambiguity: each pattern has a unique header-column signature. Verification surface: six chart renderings (three patterns × two playbooks). Risk: low-medium — the parser needs care on ranges and approximations. Dependencies: Slice 1 confirms the renderer's pattern hook is reliable.

**Slice 3 — narrative + frontmatter patterns (P19 + P23).** P19 has the strictest detection rule of any pattern in the catalogue (three concurrent conditions) and consumes free-form paragraph prose — it's the highest-risk pattern in the set. P23 reads from frontmatter, which means it depends on the P9 parser producing a `scenario_axes` shape correctly. Both patterns are also the most editorial — small detection misses can mean a chart never appears, which is a quality-of-output issue more than a correctness bug. Risk: medium. Dependencies: Slice 2 builds confidence in inline-SVG rendering and the renderer's chart pipeline.

This three-slice order means every commit lands a coherent set of patterns and the rendered playbook gets visibly richer at each step. No slice introduces a regression on the patterns that landed previously because all P18–P24 detection conditions are mutually disjoint.

---

## Markdown changes required per pattern

The intent throughout was zero markdown changes. Confirmed by line-level inspection of GOOG.md and ASML.md:

- **P18** — zero changes. Both playbooks already match the detection signature.
- **P19** — zero changes. Both §2 paragraphs match the trigger.
- **P20** — zero changes. Both §3 tables match.
- **P21** — zero changes. Both playbooks already use the `### N. Axis name` / `**The question:**` / `**Bull:**` / `**Bear:**` / `**Noise vs. structural:**` shape.
- **P22** — zero changes. All ASML and GOOG failure-mode bullets already end with `[xxx layer]`.
- **P23** — zero changes to markdown body. Frontmatter in both playbooks already populates `scenario_axes`.
- **P24** — zero changes. Both §7 tables match the `Episode | Drawdown | … | Recovery | …` signature.

If a future playbook (NFLX, AMZN, future META rewrite) follows the same conventions, the patterns activate automatically. The conventions to enforce on new playbooks are documented implicitly in the detection rules above; the catalogue entries should also be linked from a "playbook authoring conventions" note inside `/Users/anton/src/stock-review/playbooks/README.md` if one exists, or added if not.

---

## Dark-mode and print considerations

The skeleton already swaps every token via `@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)` (see html-skeleton.md lines 70–84). All P18–P24 CSS uses **only** these tokens — no hardcoded hex values — so dark mode works without per-pattern overrides. Two pattern-specific notes:

- **SVG background assumption.** P18, P23, and P24 each wrap their SVG in a parent element with `background: var(--surface)` so the chart sits on the right canvas regardless of mode. P14 (existing diagram pattern) already follows this convention. Do not omit the wrapper — an unwrapped SVG inherits `var(--bg)` from `<main>` but loses the framing.
- **Label text fill on coloured slices.** P18's segment-bar labels use `fill: var(--bg)` (line 8 of its CSS) so they invert in dark mode — light text on a dark slice fill, dark text on a light slice fill. This is the only fill where the visual contrast comes from inverting against the slice colour rather than against the page background.

**Print considerations.** The skeleton hides `aside` and expands `main` (lines 187–191). Pattern CSS does not need print rules of its own — every pattern's HTML degrades gracefully in print because (a) no pattern relies on hover state for legibility, (b) every SVG is inline and prints with the page, (c) every chart has a co-located source `<table>` or paragraph that carries the canonical data for greyscale prints where colour distinctions weaken. The one minor consideration: P18's six-token slice cycle (`accent, info, warn, ok, danger, muted`) has distinct luminance values in greyscale, so the bar is still readable in B&W; if a future playbook has >6 segments, the bar should fall through to prose (already specified in P18's "when not to use").

---

### Critical files for implementation

- `/Users/anton/src/pde-skills/references/html-patterns.md` — append P18–P24 entries here following the existing six-part structure
- `/Users/anton/src/pde-skills/references/html-skeleton.md` — token reference; pattern CSS must stay within the listed tokens
- `/Users/anton/src/stock-review/playbooks/ASML.html` — source of the existing `.axis-card` and `.fm-tag` CSS (lines 115–137) being promoted into P21/P22
- `/Users/anton/src/stock-review/playbooks/ASML.md` — canonical markdown for §4/§5 detection
- `/Users/anton/src/stock-review/playbooks/GOOG.md` — canonical markdown that currently falls through to prose; primary acceptance target

